Dude, Where's My (Stablecoin) Yield?
Kinji Steimetz

Jun 21, 2024 ⋅  11 min read

Key Insights

  • Pendle USDe and sUSDe pools offer the best return on stablecoins with APYs around 30%, driven by expectations surrounding the second Ethena airdrop.
  • Anyone who believes Morpho will launch its token at an FDV of at least $4 billion would find the yields on Morpho’s USDA vaults compelling.
  • Staking GHO in Aave’s Safety Module also offers a competitive yield driven by Aave’s Merit Program, which had an APY of 35% last month. However, depositors will take on slashing risk if the protocol incurs bad debt.
  • BounceBit’s integration with Ethena gives users access to Ethena sUSD yield while also earning BounceBit rewards.

Introduction

Over the past few weeks, I’ve been trying to figure out where I could find the best yield on stablecoins, a task which is becoming increasingly difficult due to an influx of yield sources. These include lending, providing liquidity on spot and perpetual DEXs, RWAs, and airdrop/incentive farming. It is clear that the highest yields across the space are through incentive farming and the opportunity to earn a portion of future token distribution. However, there are a limited number of opportunities to farm incentives passively, as most incentive programs are activity-based rather than liquidity-based, meaning users need to be active in interacting with the protocol to earn a decent return.

In this report, we explore the most interesting stablecoin yield pools discovered during the search, highlighting where users can find these yields and how they are generated.

Based on our research, Pendle pools offer among the best yields for stablecoins, combining high returns with guaranteed fixed yields. The highest yields are provided on USDe and sUSDE, offering just under 30% fixed APY. This yield is primarily related to the speculation around the upcoming Ethena airdrop, expected by early September, marking the end of the current Ethena SATs campaign. Ethena initially allocated 15-20% of its token supply for incentive programs, with 5-10% likely remaining available for a potential third campaign, though no official announcement has been made.

These ~30% APYs are among the highest in DeFi and come with a lower risk profile due to their fixed nature and transparent yield generation. However, these yields are short-lived, with the Pendle airdrop anticipated in early September. This gives market participants a limited guaranteed window to capture these yields and necessitates exploring other strategies afterward. I’ve compiled a list of yield opportunities and highlighted and categorized the opportunities I found most interesting.

Praying for Upside: Morpho

Some users may be willing to trade the guaranteed yield of Pendle for opportunities with greater potential upside. This involves targeting farms where rewards are distributed in tokens or points that have not yet undergone significant price discovery. Morpho presents such an opportunity at scale by incentivizing deposits with token distributions. While users can claim these tokens, they remain non-transferable until Morpho governance votes to make them so.

Morpho currently distributes rewards using its Standard Distributed Method, where tokens are allocated at an increasing rate over 90 days. Rewards are given in tandem with any additional incentives from other protocols. Thus, yields from deposits on Morpho can be threefold: from lending interest income, Morpho token rewards, and additional protocol rewards. The highest yields come from pools and vaults that capture all three sources.

Currently, the highest stablecoin APYs on Morpho are associated with USDA pools and vaults, as depositors earn both ANGLE rewards and Morpho tokens. Historically, Morpho USDA vaults run by Gauntlet and RE7 return around 15% from native lending yield and ANGLE rewards. There is potential for MORPHO to launch at a high enough FDV to make the total yield higher than that on Pendle. However, for this strategy to offer higher returns than Pendle, Morpho would need to launch around $4 billion FDV once the token becomes tradable.

Morpho's token incentive model is set to change, uniformly rewarding Morpho tokens to all deposits from regular users at a rate of 0.145 MORPHO per $1,000 per day, with a limit of $500,000 of deposits earning yield per depositor. This change will be implemented incrementally, transitioning existing rewards programs to the new model upon completion, starting with WETH, USDC, USDT, and PYUSD deployments on Ethereum.

Under the new incentive program, MORPHO would offer a 2.65% APY if the token launches at a $500 million FDV, rising to 23.82% if depositors value Morpho at $4.5 billion. These APYs would be stacked on top of any lending yield generated by deposits as well as any additional incentives from other protocols, making the yield opportunity compelling for those bullish on Morpho. However, the downside of farming Morpho is that the yield is received in the form of an illiquid position, forcing farmers to take on the price risk associated with the Morpho token. Additionally, it is uncertain when the DAO will vote to make the token transferable.

One Season Away: Aave and BounceBit

While the best APYs in crypto are currently provided directly by Pendle, there are other sources offering competitive yields from alternative sources. Although these opportunities cannot match Pendle's yields at present, they are likely to maintain high APYs after the Pendle pools expire.

Aave Safety Module: GHO

One potential source of yield is Aave’s stablecoin GHO. GHO is an overcollateralized stablecoin backed by a basket of crypto assets. It is minted similarly to DAI, where users deposit collateral assets accepted on the Aave lending protocol. Instead of users depositing GHO to the platform, the protocol mints new supply, creating a stablecoin backed by the collateral assets. Aave also plans to implement a stability module similar to DAI’s PSM, where users can swap GHO for other governance-approved stablecoins at a fixed 1:1 ratio to help maintain the $1 peg. Currently, GHO has a collateralization ratio of 250%, which is comparable to DAI’s 266%.

In November 2023, the Aave DAO voted to add GHO as a second asset alongside Aave to be accepted by the Aave Safety Module. This allows GHO to be staked as a backstop against the protocol taking on bad debt. Currently, about 60% ($59 million) of the GHO supply is staked in the Aave Safety Module. Stakers in the Safety Module take on additional risk, as their funds can be used to mitigate any bad debt the protocol incurs. For instance, Aave incurred approximately $1.6 million in bad debt following the Avraham Eisenberg attack. Staking GHO carries higher risk than staking Aave because GHO deposits can be fully slashed in the case of bad debt, meaning depositors have 100% of their value at risk. In contrast, Aave token depositors can only be slashed up to 50%, equating to 50% of their value at risk.

Stakers of GHO in Aave’s Safety Module are compensated for the slashing risk through two yield sources. The first is Aave token emissions, currently set at 50 AAVE per day, distributed across all staked GHO. The second source of yield is Aave’s Merit Program, a reward mechanism designed to enhance Aave's appeal and efficiency. It rewards specific actions like borrowing wETH or GHO, holding stkGHO, and active governance participation while disincentivizing engagement with non-aligned protocols such as Morpho. The program heavily promotes GHO by subsidizing its minting and creating an incentive to hold GHO through competitive yields for GHO stakers.

The backend calculations for how Aave rewards users are not yet open source, so the market doesn’t know exactly how rewards are generated or allocated. However, based on historical TVL and APY, it appears the program is emitting roughly $750K in GHO rewards to the staking pool each month, resulting in a competitive APYs for stakers, with the current set of rewards expected to provide an APY of 21.25% and the previous epoch returning an APY of 35.23%. Aave DAO members have stated intentions to open-source the Merit Program calculation at a later, undetermined date.

While staking GHO in the Safety Module is producing APYs that are competitive with Pendle USDe yields, GHO staking comes with additional risks. These include the above-mentioned risk of slashing in the event of Aave taking on bad debt and a lack of transparency regarding the distribution of future rewards.

BounceBit x Ethena

BounceBit launched as a protocol granting users access to a BTC-based cash and carry trade, that allows users to allocate capital to centralized trading firms that then execute the cash and carry trade in exchange for a fee. Since its launch, BounceBit has made two significant announcements that make it a potentially interesting farming opportunity. First, they launched their own PoS Layer-1, providing a source of native yield by allowing users to allocate either BB, the protocol's native token, or BTC to one of the 25 validators currently maintaining the network.

Second, BounceBit announced an integration with Ethena, allowing users to deposit their BBUSD, a wrapped stablecoin mapped to USDT, on BounceBit to Ethena. As a result, users generate yield from BounceBit validator rewards, yield generated by Ethena, and participation in Ethena’s SATs campaign, earning 5x SATs per day. So far, the integration has accumulated $23.84 million in TVL.

At present, despite the lower rate of 5x SATs per day compared to the 20-30x SATs rewarded for other actions, BounceBit’s partnership with Ethena is able to offer a similar total APY of around 25% to what is offered on Pendle for future USDe yield. However, accessing Ethena through BounceBit could become more enticing following the conclusion of Ethena Season 2. Users would continue to earn Ethena yields, which are likely to remain among the most competitive in DeFi, as well as BounceBit rewards. Currently, BounceBit rewards are around an APY of 6-7% in the form of BounceBit’s BB token. The combined APY will likely be lower than what is currently being offered on Pendle due to the absence of a future airdrop associated with that yield. However, based on a sUSDe rate of 15%, accessing Ethena through BounceBit could offer yields of upwards of 20%.

It's worth noting that BounceBit is the newest protocol mentioned in this report, having launched its Mainnet in May. This recent launch may signal a higher level of risk to potential farmers due to the inherent uncertainties in new codebases.

In the table above, we highlighted some additional pools providing competitive APYs from sources outside of Ethena, which are worth exploring. Here are some notable options:

  • Aries Market Lending Pools: Native lending yield is around 5%, but depositors receive additional yield in the form of Aptos token rewards.
  • Ekubo Stablecoin DEX Pools: The USDC-USDT liquidity pools are primarily used to farm Starknet rewards.
  • Blast Futures and Synthetix: Providing liquidity to derivatives protocols carries more risk compared to alternative options, as these vaults perform market-making strategies that can result in drawdowns.
  • Aerodrome and Beefy: Aerodrome incentivizes liquidity provision to its token pairs through Aero rewards. Users can either provide liquidity directly or use Beefy as a frontend yield aggregator.

Closing Thoughts

In recent weeks, I've been searching for the best stablecoin yields, focusing on passive strategies that require minimal monitoring or management. The search led me to USDe and sUSDe Pendle pools, which offer competitive yields driven by a second ENA airdrop and the security of a fixed yield. However, these high APYs are only guaranteed for a short period, with Ethena’s second airdrop expected in early September. While Ethena has tokens reserved for future incentive programs, it’s worth monitoring the ecosystem for alternative yield opportunities that could rival Pendle yields or become competitive post-airdrop.

Morpho offers an opportunity for bullish investors, providing rewards in the form of lending yield, non-transferable Morpho tokens, and rewards from other protocols. Currently, rewards are allocated to specific pools, but Morpho will soon transition to an incentive program rewarding all retail deposits at a uniform rate. Depending on the expected FDV at launch, APYs could exceed 20% when combining Morpho rewards with native lending yield and additional protocol rewards.

Aave's Merit Program is incentivizing GHO growth by boosting yields for users who stake GHO in the Aave Safety Module. While the reward calculation methodology is not open-sourced, Aave appears to be distributing approximately $750K per month to GHO stakers, resulting in an estimated APY of 22%. However, GHO staking carries slashing risk if Aave incurs bad debt.

Despite the second Ethena airdrop driving high Pendle yields, Ethena should remain a competitive source of stablecoin yield post-airdrop, as sUSDe holders receive a portion of carry trade profits. Yields can become even more enticing if users can stack additional rewards on top of their sUSDe yield. BounceBit offers such an opportunity through an Ethena integration, allowing users to deposit into Ethena via BounceBit to earn sUSDe yield plus rewards in BounceBit’s native BB token, which has averaged around 7% in additional yield.
